'''Ōmiwa Shrine''' (おおみわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Kamiishizu-chō, {{ill|lt=Ōgaki|Q384926|WD=Q384926|1=Ōgaki}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|WD=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}.

It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} of Tagi District, {{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|WD=Q864156|1=Mino Province}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. It is one of the many {{ill|lt=Ōmiwa Shrines|Q705542|WD=Q705542|1=Ōmiwa Shrine}} in Japan.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|WD=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi|Q10936701|WD=Q10936701|WD=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi Kushimikatama-no-Mikoto|1=Ōmononushi}}

Associated deities
*{{ill|lt=Emperor Jinmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188|lt=Kamuyamatoiwarehiko-no-Sumeramikoto|1=Emperor Jimmu}}
*{{ill|lt=Himetataraisuzuhime|Q5353793|WD=Q5353793|lt=Himetataraisuzuhime-no-Mikoto|1=Himetataraisuzu-hime}}

=== History ===
*The founding date is unknown. During the reign of {{ill|lt=Empress Jitō|Q232026|WD=Q232026|1=Empress Jitō}}, when she reached Yokkaichi District in {{ill|lt=Ise Province|Q864166|WD=Q864166|1=Ise Province}} on an imperial progress to Ise, Right Minister Miwa no Ason Takachimaro received an oracle from Ōmononushi Kushimikatama-no-Mikoto and founded this shrine on Mt. Tagi in Mino Province. It was originally called Ōmiwa Shrine.
*In {{ill|lt=1113|Q19531|WD=Q19531|1=1113}} (Eikyū 1), a nearby shrine was washed to this shrine in a violent storm. The deity of that shrine (Emperor Jinmu and Himetataraisuzuhime-no-Mikoto) was merged here, and the name was changed to Nagarehiko Daimyōjin.
*In {{ill|lt=1375|Q6277|WD=Q6277|1=1375}} (Eiwa 7), it was moved to the current site.
*In {{ill|lt=1869|Q7720|WD=Q7720|1=1869}} (Meiji 2), it resumed the name Ōmiwa Shrine; in Meiji 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it became gōsha.

=== Cultural properties ===
'''Gifu Prefecture designated natural monument'''
*Shrine grove of Ōmiwa Shrine<ref>{{Cite web|和書|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/tenki/oogakisi/oomiwa.html |title=Shrine grove of Ōmiwa Shrine |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref>

=== Access ===
*From {{ill|lt=Sekigahara Station|Q872034|WD=Q872034|1=Sekigahara Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Tōkaidō Main Line|Q1190152|WD=Q1190152|1=Tōkaidō Main Line}}, take the {{ill|lt=Meihan Kintetsu Bus|Q11415818|WD=Q11415818|1=Meihan Kintetsu Bus}} Sekigahara-Toki line and get off at “Miya.”

=== Nearby facilities ===
*{{ill|lt=Nishitakagi Family Jinya|Q11630008|WD=Q11630008|1=Nishitakagike Jin'ya}}

=== Other ===
*Shrine tradition gives the founding year as Shuchō 6, but that year does not exist. Since Shuchō 1 is {{ill|lt=686|Q30619|WD=Q30619|1=686}}, “Shuchō 6” is estimated around {{ill|lt=691|Q23474|WD=Q23474|1=691}}, suggesting a late 7th-century foundation.
*The current site is in former Ishi District, Mino Province. It moved here in Eiwa 7; before that it is said to have been at a place called Uenoyama.

